Policy Iteration & Value Iteration (Grid World)

This project implements two fundamental reinforcement learning algorithms—Policy Iteration and Value Iteration—on a 5x5 grid-world environment. The objective is to compute optimal state values and policies that guide an agent to terminal states while minimizing cost.

The environment consists of a grid with two terminal states at opposite corners. Each move results in a negative reward, encouraging the agent to reach terminal states in the fewest steps. Actions include moving up, down, left, and right, with boundary constraints.

Part 1: Policy Iteration

Policy Iteration alternates between two steps:

Policy Evaluation: The value function is updated iteratively based on the current policy until convergence.
Policy Improvement: The policy is updated by selecting actions that maximize expected returns.

The process repeats until the policy stabilizes. During execution, value matrices and policy updates are printed at each iteration, and error values are tracked to visualize convergence.

Part 2: Value Iteration

Value Iteration directly computes optimal state values using the Bellman optimality equation. At each iteration, state values are updated by selecting the maximum expected return over all possible actions.

The algorithm continues until the change in values falls below a threshold, indicating convergence. Final state values are displayed, and error values per iteration are plotted to show convergence behavior.

Outputs
State Value Matrices (per iteration and final)
Optimal Policy (Policy Iteration)
Error vs. Iteration Graphs
Tech Stack
Python
NumPy
Matplotlib
